{"cursor":"12379","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Hudson River Chain' refers to two chains and two [[cheval de frise|chevaux\nde frise]] constructed from 1776 to 1778 during the American Revolutionary War\nacross the Hudson River as defenses to prevent British naval vessels from\nsailing upriver. These defenses along the Hudson River were overseen by the\nHighlands Department of the Continental Army. The most significant and\nsuccessful was the Great Chain, constructed from West Point in 1778, and used\nthrough 1782 after the war's end. The huge links for the chains were forged at\niron works in Orange County, New York.\n","linknr":380,"url":"Hudson_River_Chain","recorded":1362476874,"links":23,"instances":["sailing","westchester","hudson_river","new_york"],"pdf":["http://www.hudsonrivervalley.org/books/Chainandboom.pdf"],"categories":["United States Military Academy","New York in the American Revolution","American Revolutionary War","Visitor attractions in Orange County, New York","U.S. Route 9W","Military in New York","Hudson River"],"headings":["Background","Fort Washington's ''chevaux-de-frise'' (1776)","Fort Montgomery Chain (1776-1777)","Pollepel Island's chevaux-de-frise (1776-1777)","The Great Chain (1778-1782)","Bibliography","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/1/1c/West_Point_Fortifications.jpg/220px-West_Point_Fortifications.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/73/Fields_of_Fire_from_Fort_Constitution.jpg/220px-Fields_of_Fire_from_Fort_Constitution.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/75/The_Great_Chain_Sketch.jpg/220px-The_Great_Chain_Sketch.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/9f/The_Great_Chain_Today.JPG/220px-The_Gre